dustry? How should the South African economy and mining\n                                industry be reset?\n                            \nIn his keynote address Mxolisi Mgojo reflected on the mining industry\xe2\x80\x99s response to COVID-19 and the lessons learned.\nPresentation\nKeynote address\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nUpcoming event: Masoyise workplace health virtual seminar\nFighting the unrecognised pandemic: Reprioritising TB, HIV and NCDs in the era of COVID-19\n\n                                The Masoyise Health Programme is a multi-stakeholder initiative led by the Minerals Council to reduce the impact of TB, HIV, occupational lung diseases and non-communicable diseases as occupational health\n                                threats in the mining sector.\n                                Join Minerals Council South Africa in discussion with Minister of Health, Dr Zweli Mkhize and experts from UNAIDS, ILO and the WHO as they share solutions to resolve this problem.\n                            \nRegister to attend the seminar on 15 October 2020 at 11:00 \xe2\x80\x93 14:00 CAT\nSpeakers include:\n\n\nDr Zweli Mkhize: Minister of Health, South Africa\nDr Shannon Hader: Deputy Executive Director UNAIDS\nDr Owen Kaluwa: WHO Representative to South Africa\n\n\nMs Zanele Matlala: Vice President Minerals Council South Africa and Masoyise Health Programme Chair\nMs Alette van Leur: Director Sectoral Policies Department, ILO\n\n\nRead more\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n                        The Minerals Council South Africa launched the first National Day of Women in Mining highlighting its focus on the implementation of initiatives designed to achieve stretch targets for the representation and\n                        advancement of women in the South African mining industry.\n                    \nMedia Release\nPresentation\nVideo\nRead more\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMINERALS COUNCIL SUPPORTS B4SA INITIATIVE TO REVITALISE SA ECONOMY AND MINING POST COVID-19\n\n\n\n\n\n                                The Minerals Council South Africa supports the accelerated economic strategy developed under the auspices of B4SA aimed at achieving much higher levels of inclusive economic growth to recover from the\n                                COVID-19 crisis, and the economic crisis that preceded it.\n                            \nRead more\n\n\nFor more information in the Minerals Council position on COVID-19, visit our dedicated COVID-19 portal\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe Minerals Council recognises that the accessibility of information and transparency is critical.\n\n                        The industry\xe2\x80\x99s approach to reporting on incidents of COVID-19 is aligned to the requirements of the DoH in the first instance, while keeping the DMRE, the MHSC and organised labour informed at all times.\n                    \n\nFor more information, visit our COVID-19 portal\n\n\n\nFor further information on COVID-19, please visit www.sacoronavirus.co.za\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nClose\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPrevious\n\n\n\nNext\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\xc3\x97\nMinerals Council South Africa: Impact of Planned Carbon Tax\n\n\n\n\n\nClose\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nLATEST NEWS\n\nMinerals Council South Africa publishes Facts and Figures 2019 October 08, 2020READ MOREMasoyise Health Programme calls for reprioritisation of pre-existing occupational health threats in the era of COVID-19 October 07, 2020READ MOREMinerals Council welcomes President Ramaphosa\xe2\x80\x99s call to rebuild South African economy September 18, 2020READ MORE \n\n\nFACEBOOK\n\n\nLike us @Mine\n\n1 days ago Bizcommunity: Reprioritising existing occupational health threats in a time of Covid-19\n\nhttps://www...3 days ago City Press: Covid-19: A chance for mining to be innovative \nhttps://www.news24.com/citypress/voices/...6 days ago African Mining Market: Masoyise Health Programme calls for reprioritisation of preexisting occupatio...6 days a